Oh, I&#39;m not offended or anything of the sort.  I&#39;m just chuckling that
you and I specifically have discussed this issue before.  I&#39;m a quick
typist, and I ought to be: I have all this practice from documenting
my test methods and assert statements!  :)

&gt; 
&gt; &gt; Just like the test name often needs further clarification (never pass
&gt; &gt; up an oportunity for documentation), often the reason for the
&gt; &gt; assertion is not self-apparent.  You can try to argue that &quot;it ought
&gt; &gt; to be, or rewrite your code!&quot; but, as before, I think you&#39;re straying
&gt; &gt; too close to the &quot;Java code is self-documenting&quot; argument, which I
&gt; &gt; find ... dubious at best.
&gt; 
&gt; I don&#39;t know. I just wrote this in an XHTMLUnit test today:
&gt; 
&gt; assertXpathExists(
&gt;      somewhereThereIsA(formNamed(&quot;demographics&quot;))
&gt;      .eventuallyContainingA(textFieldNamed(&quot;firstName&quot;)), document);
&gt; 
&gt; This translated to the XPath expression
&gt; 
&gt;      //form[@name=&quot;demographics&quot;]//input[@type=&quot;text&quot; and @name=&quot;firstName&quot;]
&gt; 
&gt; Is a comment or a failure message going to make that clearer?

I haven&#39;t had a need for XHTMLUnit, I&#39;m mostly commenting about
vanilla JUnit usage.  That said, what message does the above generate
in your error report?

&gt;&gt; Or to put it pithily:
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; I feel that I&#39;m proficient with Java, but when I want to explain
&gt; &gt; something, especially *why* something, I generally prefer English.
&gt; 
&gt; I agree and explain &quot;why&quot; in English, but nost of the time, test case
&gt; class name, method name and line number is enough for me to know what
&gt; failed, from which I generally can determine why it failed. If not, then
&gt; my tests are too big (and that&#39;s an entirely different problem).

Do you have the same experience with tests you&#39;re not the author of? 
This is where I&#39;ve found it especially helpful, or frustrating if it
doesn&#39;t exist.  Of course *my* logic and reasoning is always obvious,
it&#39;s those other punks that write stuff I can&#39;t understand. 
(sarcasm!)

These additional comments have also been helpful if I&#39;m debugging a
section I neither wrote, nor studied the original requirements.  An
example of that situation is code written for features implemented
before I joined the proeject.

-Kevin
